Building GriffinEvo

I took the opportunity of building this page to practice using R, RMarkdown, HTML, CSS and JavaScript. Each page on this site is created by an RMarkdown document (.Rmd). Each of those .Rmd documents contains a connection to three HTML documents — in_header.html, before_body.html and after_body.html. These are connected to by the YAML header of each .Rmd document which looks like

---
title: Page Title
output: 
  html_document:
    theme: null
    includes:
      in_header:   in_header.html
      before_body: before_body.html
      after_body:  after_body.html
---

These include options are used when the document is rendered by the rmarkdown package. When rendered, R will add these documents to each .Rmd file in the way you would expect from their names:

  • before_body.html contains HTML elements that create the top bar and the navigation menu — elements that will occur prior to the main content of each page, e.g.
<div id="nav-menu-container">
  <div id="close-nav"  onclick="closeNav()">Close</div>
  <ul class="nav-list">
    <li><a class="nav-link" href="index.html">Home</a></li>
    <li class="icon-container">
      <a href="https://twitter.com/griffinevo" target="_blank" class="fa fa-twitter-square navLink"></a>
      <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/robgriffin247/" target="_blank" class="fa-linkedin-square navLink fa"></a>
      <a href="https://github.com/griffinevo" target="_blank" class="fa fa-github-square navLink"></a>
      <a href="mailto:robgriffin247@hotmail.com" class="fa fa-envelope-square navLink"></a>
    </li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="top-bar">
  <div class="site-title">GriffinEvo</div>
  <div id="open-nav" onclick="openNav()">Menu</div>
</div>

<div id="overlay"></div>
  • after_body.html contains elements to occur after the main content of each page (and is currently empty)
  • in_header.html contains information for the HTML head, such as encoding, JavaScript for functions making the page interactive (e.g. the navigation menu) and a link to a stylesheet, e.g.
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

The stylesheet is the fourth and final central document. It is a CSS document specifying how HTML elements will be styled on the page (beyond default behaviours), e.g.

@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Nunito:ital,wght@0,200;0,300;0,400;0,500;0,600;1,200;1,300;1,400;1,500;1,600&display=swap');

:root {
  --pridark:  #104e47;
  --primid:   #417a72;
  --prilight: #6fa9a0;
  --secdark:  #c42b00;
  --secmid:   #ff6004;
  --seclight: #ff9240;
}

body {
  width: 92%;
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  font-size: 12pt;
  padding: 3em 0 10em 0;
  font-family: 'Nunito', sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.8em;
  font-weight: 300;
  overflow-y: scroll;
}

Finally, I have a short R script that picks up each .Rmd document in the directory and sends it to the render() function in R and renders the entire site, allowing any changes to style or generic elements (such as the menu when adding new pages) to be applied to all pages.

lapply(list.files()[grepl(".Rmd", list.files())], render)

I find this way of making and maintaining my website very convenient as it allows the common components such as the navigation menu to be easily updated and modified across the site. If you would like any advice on how to use this same approach, please get in touch!
